3 Oridnary Least Squares:

To test the relationship between child poverty and our independent variables we will start by running a simple OLS. This equation will be used to explain the level of child poverty by the list of variables and log variables in the dataset. We are also going to limit the use of scientific notation to numbers greater than 5 decimal places within the output and summaries.

equation <- child.pov.2016 ~ rural + urban + lnmanufacturing + lnag + 
  lnretail + lnhealthss + lnconstruction + lnlesshs + 
  lnunemployment + lnsinglemom + lnblack + lnhispanic + 
  lnuninsured + lnincome_ratio + lnteenbirth + lnunmarried
#Write as an object to keep from having to write it over and over 

options(scipen = 5)

ols <- lm(equation, data=md_pov)
summary(ols)

None of the independent variables show up as significant based on the OLS analysis. The model itself, however, has a p-value of 0.003. What this might suggest is that our dataset for child poverty in Maryland is probably not dependent on any of these factors spatially within the state, but perhaps the nature of Marylands closeness to several other nearby states and large cities (with large wealth inequalities, like Baltimore), could be having an influence of the models fit.

#determining underlying spatial relationships in our residuals:
fips <- county.fips
fips.codes <- separate(data = fips, col = polyname, into = c("state", "county"), sep = ",")
md_fips <- subset(fips.codes, state=="maryland", select=fips)
maryland <- map(database = "county", regions = "maryland", fill=T, plot=F)
md_sp = map2SpatialPolygons(maryland,md_fips$fips,CRS("+proj=longlat"))
#When running the next step of the process to create a list of neighbors for each county in the dataset, an error message stated that the polygons had invalid geometry. This means that when the data was digitized one of the polygons might not have been closed or there are overlapping vertices or lines. This can be repaired with the cleangeo package that somewhat acts like janitor but for spatial data.
cleaned <- clgeo_Clean(md_sp)
## Warning in proj4string(sp): CRS object has comment, which is lost in output
neighb.data <- poly2nb(cleaned, queen=T)
cont.neighb <- nb2listw(neighb.data,style="W", zero.policy = TRUE)
#Now that we have created a spatial dataset and a list of neighbors, we can determine if there is any residual spatial dependence.

4 Morans Correlation Test

In this step we will use a Morans Correlation Test designed for regression residuals to examines the residuals of the OLS regression using the spatial relationship matrix. In this case the null hypothesis (HO) is no spatial correlation in the residuals.

lm.morantest(ols, cont.neighb)
## 
##  Global Moran I for regression residuals
## 
## data:  
## model: lm(formula = equation, data = md_pov)
## weights: cont.neighb
## 
## Moran I statistic standard deviate = 0.3672, p-value = 0.3567
## alternative hypothesis: greater
## sample estimates:
## Observed Moran I      Expectation         Variance 
##      -0.10498509      -0.15879073       0.02147037

Non-significant p-value, which tells us that we dont need some kind of spatial model for analysis. Just a regression analysis works to explain these data.

Just to check all possible spatial model types, we can run a SARMA hypothetical test. Most often, this kind of analysis isnt very applicable. It runs all of the possible different types of models (seasonal auto-regressive moving)

lm.LMtests(ols, cont.neighb, test="all")
##

The SARMA test agrees with my Morans test (non-significant), which means we can stop with the OLS model. This suggests that child poverty in the state of Maryland is not dependent on the spatial relationships between neighboring counties.

Spatial durbin = global effects Spatial durbin error = local effects

5 Mapping the results

#dist.lag.data <- summary(all.dist.lag.k1, correlation=TRUE, Nagelkerke = TRUE)

dist.lag.output <- cbind.data.frame(md_pov$FIPS,
                                   md_pov$child.pov.2016, 
                                    md_pov$lnmanufacturing, 
                                    md_pov$lnblack, 
                                    md_pov$lnlesshs, 
                                    md_pov$lnhispanic,
                                    stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

#Renaming columns
colnames(dist.lag.output) <- c("fips","childpov",
                        "manufacturing","black","less_hs","hispanic")
md_fortify <- fortify(md_sp)

md_poly <- merge(x = md_fortify, y = dist.lag.output, 
                 by.x = "id", by.y = "fips", all = TRUE)

bivariate_data <- bi_class(md_poly, x = childpov, y = less_hs, 
                           dim = 3, style = "quantile")

legend <- bi_legend(pal = "DkViolet",
                    dim = 3,
                    xlab = "Child Poverty",
                    ylab = "Less-than Highschool Education",
                    size = 6)
#Now that we have data and a legend, we need to create additional datasets to serve as a basemap for our analysis.

world <- map_data("world")
states <- map_data("state")
southern_states <- subset(states, region %in% 
                            c("texas", "arkansas", "louisiana", "mississippi", 
                              "alabama", "georgia", "florida", "north carolina",
                              "south carolina", "tennessee", "oklahoma", 
                              "kentucky", "west virginia", "virginia", 
                              "maryland", "delaware", "district of columbia"))
mom_pov_map <- ggplot() + 
  geom_polygon(data = world, aes(x=long,y=lat, group=group), fill = "gray95", color = "white") +
  geom_polygon(data = states, aes(x=long,y=lat, group=group), fill = "gray", color = "white") +
  geom_polygon(data = southern_states, aes(x=long,y=lat, group=group), fill = NA, size = 0.01, color = "white") +  
  geom_polygon(data = bivariate_data, aes(x=long, y=lat, group=group, fill = bi_class), color = "grey50", show.legend = FALSE) + 
  bi_scale_fill(pal = "DkViolet", dim = 3) +
  coord_map("conic", lat0 = 30, xlim=c(-79.6,-75), ylim=c(37.7,40)) +
  theme_void() + theme(legend.title.align=0.5) +
  theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = 'deepskyblue'),
        panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = NA)) +
  labs(x = "Longitude", y = "Latitude", fill = "Child Poverty", 
       title = "Bivariate Map of Child Poverty and Less-than Highschool Education") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", hjust = 0.5))
final_map <- ggdraw() +
  draw_plot(mom_pov_map, 0, 0, 1, 1) +
  draw_plot(legend, 0.150, 0.030, 0.25, 0.75)
